Readme.md
    42‚Üí### Usage
    44‚ÜíSuperstruct allows you to define the shape of data you want to validate:
    45‚Üí
    46‚Üí```js
    47‚Üíimport { assert, object, number, string, array } from 'superstruct'
    48‚Üí
    49‚Üíconst Article = object({
      ‚Üí‚Ä¶
   145‚Üí### Why?
   147‚ÜíThere are lots of existing validation libraries‚Äî[`joi`](https://github.com/hapijs/joi), [`express-validator`](https://github.com/ctavan/express-validator), [`validator.js`](https://github.com/chriso/validator.js), [`yup`](https://github.com/jquense/yup), [`ajv`](https://github.com/epoberezkin/ajv), [`is-my-json-valid`](https://github.com/mafintosh/is-my-json-valid)... But they exhibit many issues that lead to your codebase becoming hard to maintain...
   148‚Üí
   149‚Üí- **They don't expose detailed errors.** Many validators simply return string-only errors or booleans without any details as to why, making it difficult to customize the errors to be helpful for end-users.
   150‚Üí
   151‚Üí- **They make custom types hard.** Many validators ship with built-in types like emails, URLs, UUIDs, etc. with no way to know what they check for, and complicated APIs for defining new types.
   152‚Üí
      ‚Üí‚Ä¶
   167‚Üí### Principles
   169‚Üí1. **Customizable types.** Superstruct's power is in making it easy to define an entire set of custom data types that are specific to your application, and defined in a _single_ place, so you have full control over your requirements.
   170‚Üí
   171‚Üí2. **Unopinionated defaults.** Superstruct ships with native JavaScript types, and everything else is customizable, so you never have to fight to override decisions made by "core" that differ from your application's needs.
   172‚Üí
   173‚Üí3. **Composable interfaces.** Superstruct interfaces are composable, so you can break down commonly-repeated pieces of data into components, and compose them to build up the more complex objects.
   174‚Üí
      ‚Üí‚Ä¶
   181‚Üí### Demo
   183‚ÜíTry out the [live demo on CodeSandbox](https://codesandbox.io/s/bold-water-s2cr8d?file=/index.js) to get an idea for how the API works, or to quickly verify your use case:
   184‚Üí
   185‚Üí[![Demo screenshot.](./docs/images/demo-screenshot.png)](https://codesandbox.io/s/bold-water-s2cr8d?file=/index.js)
   186‚Üí
   187‚Üí<br/>
   188‚Üí
   189‚Üí### Examples
   191‚ÜíSuperstruct's API is very flexible, allowing it to be used for a variety of use cases on your servers and in the browser. Here are a few examples of common patterns...
   192‚Üí
   193‚Üí- [Basic Validation](./examples/basic-validation.js)
   194‚Üí- [Custom Types](./examples/custom-types.js)
   195‚Üí- [Default Values](./examples/default-values.js)
   196‚Üí- [Optional Values](./examples/optional-values.js)
      ‚Üí‚Ä¶
   205‚Üí### Documentation
   207‚ÜíRead the getting started guide to familiarize yourself with how Superstruct works. After that, check out the full API reference for more detailed information about structs, types and errors...
   208‚Üí
   209‚Üí- [**Guide**](https://docs.superstructjs.org/guides/01-getting-started)
   210‚Üí  - [Getting Started](https://docs.superstructjs.org/guides/01-getting-started)
   211‚Üí  - [Validating Data](https://docs.superstructjs.org/guides/02-validating-data)
   212‚Üí  - [Coercing Data](https://docs.superstructjs.org/guides/03-coercing-data)
