docs/readme.md
     7‚Üí### Usage
     9‚ÜíSuperstruct allows you to define the shape of data you want to validate:
    10‚Üí
    11‚Üí```js
    12‚Üíimport { assert, object, number, string, array } from 'superstruct'
    13‚Üí
    14‚Üíconst Article = object({
    15‚Üí  id: number(),
    16‚Üí  title: string(),
    17‚Üí  tags: array(string()),
    18‚Üí  author: object({
    19‚Üí    id: number(),
    20‚Üí  }),
    21‚Üí})
    22‚Üí
    23‚Üíconst data = {
    24‚Üí  id: 34,
    25‚Üí  title: 'Hello World',
    26‚Üí  tags: ['news', 'features'],
    27‚Üí  author: {
    28‚Üí    id: 1,
    29‚Üí  },
    30‚Üí}
    31‚Üí
    32‚Üíassert(data, Article)
    33‚Üí// This will throw an error when the data is invalid.
    34‚Üí// If you'd rather not throw, you can use `is()` or `validate()`.
    35‚Üí```
    36‚Üí
    37‚ÜíSuperstruct ships with validators for all the common JavaScript data types, and you can define custom ones too:
    38‚Üí
    39‚Üí```js
    40‚Üíimport { is, define, object, string } from 'superstruct'
    41‚Üíimport isUuid from 'is-uuid'
    42‚Üíimport isEmail from 'is-email'
    43‚Üí
    44‚Üíconst Email = define('Email', isEmail)
    45‚Üíconst Uuid = define('Uuid', isUuid.v4)
    46‚Üí
    47‚Üíconst User = object({
    48‚Üí  id: Uuid,
    49‚Üí  email: Email,
    50‚Üí  name: string(),
    51‚Üí})
    52‚Üí
    53‚Üíconst data = {
    54‚Üí  id: 'c8d63140-a1f7-45e0-bfc6-df72973fea86',
    55‚Üí  email: 'jane@example.com',
    56‚Üí  name: 'Jane',
    57‚Üí}
    58‚Üí
    59‚Üíif (is(data, User)) {
    60‚Üí  // Your data is guaranteed to be valid in this block.
    61‚Üí}
    62‚Üí```
    63‚Üí
    64‚ÜíSuperstruct can also handle coercion of your data before validating it, for example to mix in default values:
    65‚Üí
    66‚Üí```ts
    67‚Üíimport { create, object, number, string, defaulted } from 'superstruct'
    68‚Üí
    69‚Üíconst User = object({
    70‚Üí  id: defaulted(number(), () => 1),
    71‚Üí  name: string(),
    72‚Üí})
    73‚Üí
    74‚Üíconst data = {
    75‚Üí  name: 'Jane',
    76‚Üí}
    77‚Üí
    78‚Üí// You can apply the defaults to your data while validating.
    79‚Üíconst user = create(data, User)
    80‚Üí// {
    81‚Üí//   id: 1,
    82‚Üí//   name: 'Jane',
    83‚Üí// }
    84‚Üí```
    85‚Üí
      ‚Üí‚Ä¶
docs/reference/core.md
     3‚Üí### `assert`
     5‚Üí`assert<T>(value: unknown, struct: Struct<T>, message?: string) => asserts value is T`
     6‚Üí
     7‚Üí```ts
     8‚Üíassert(value, User, 'The user is invalid!')
     9‚Üí```
    10‚Üí
    11‚ÜíAssert that `value` is valid according to a `struct`. If the value is invalid a [`StructError`](./errors.md#structerror) will be thrown (the optional `message` parameter allows you to override error's message).
    12‚Üí
    13‚Üí> ü§ñ When using TypeScript `assert` acts as an [assertion function](https://www.typescriptlang.org/docs/handbook/release-notes/typescript-3-7.html#assertion-functions), so you can ensure that after calling it the type of the `value` matches the shape of the struct.
    14‚Üí
docs/reference/typescript.md
     7‚Üí### `Describe`
     9‚ÜíThe `Describe` utility returns a type representing a struct for a given valid value type. This allows you to ensure you're writing your struct definitions properly, for example:
    10‚Üí
    11‚Üí```ts
    12‚Üítype User = {
    13‚Üí  id: number
    14‚Üí  name: string
    15‚Üí}
    16‚Üí
    17‚Üíconst User: Describe<User> = object({
    18‚Üí  id: string(), // This mistake will fail to pass type checking!
    19‚Üí  name: string(),
    20‚Üí})
    21‚Üí```
    22‚Üí
      ‚Üí‚Ä¶
docs/resources/faq.md
     1‚Üí# FAQ
     3‚ÜíSome common questions you might have when first learning Superstruct.
     4‚Üí
     5‚Üí### How can I allow unknown keys with `object` structs?
     7‚ÜíThe [`object`](../reference/types.md#object) struct validates that a value matches a known object shape. Just like it's TypeScript counterpart, it does not allow unknown keys‚Äîthis is very useful in catching bugs in the majority of cases.
     8‚Üí
      ‚Üí‚Ä¶
    11‚Üí### Why not have a built-in `json` struct?
    13‚ÜíThe problem with a built-in `json` struct is that it needs to recursively iterate through deep objects to guarantee they're valid JSON. What's wrong with that? Nothing, except that it would be a footgun.
    14‚Üí
      ‚Üí‚Ä¶
